{"title_page": "Indiana Beach", "text_new": "{{short description|American amusement park}}\n{{For|the unincorporated community where the park is located|Indiana Beach, Indiana}}{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Indiana Beach\n| logo = IndianaBeach logo.png\n| logo_size = 300px\n| caption = \n| location = [[Monticello, Indiana|Monticello]], [[White County, Indiana|White County]]\n| location2 = Indiana\n| location3 = United States\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.79|N|86.77|W|display=inline,title}}\n| owner = [[Apex Parks Group]]\n| opening_date = 1926\n| season = May through October\n| rides = 43\n| coasters = 5\n| area_ acre = 10\n| address = 5224 East Indiana Beach Blvd <br /> Monticello, Indiana 47960\n| previous_name(s) = Ideal Beach; Indiana Beach Amusement Resort\n| water_slides = 4\n| slogan = ''\"Where Families Flock For Fun\"'' (previously: ''\"There's more than corn in Indiana!\"'' & ''\"The riviera of the midwest!\"'')\n| homepage = http://www.indianabeach.com\n| status = Open\n}}\n\n'''Indiana Beach''' is an amusement park located on [[Lake Shafer]] in [[Monticello, Indiana]]. The resort was developed by the Spackman family, who owned it from 1926 to 2008. The park was then sold to Morgan RV LLC, who sold it to Apex Parks Group in 2015. Apex announced Indiana Beach's closure in February 2020. Following Apex Parks' bankruptcy in April 2020, the park's social media began teasing a possible reopening, with an announcement on April 23rd that the park would be open for the 2020 season.\n\n== History ==\nOriginally named Ideal Beach, the [[amusement park]] began as a small lakeside beach with a bath house and refreshment stand. In 1927, the first thrill attraction opened, and from that point, it began to expand.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/life/2016/07/04/indiana-beach-new-beginning/86153880/|title=For Indiana Beach, a new beginning|last=Grady|first=Danielle|date=July 4, 2016|website=IndyStar|access-date=}}</ref> In the 1930s and 1940s, it was popular for the Ideal Beach Ballroom, featuring well-known bands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianabeach.com/pages/indianabeach_history#|title=Indiana Beach Amusement Resort: History|last=|first=|date=|website=Indiana Beach|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101012642/http://www.indianabeach.com/pages/indianabeach_history|archive-date=November 1, 2013|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref> In February 2008, it was announced that both the amusement park and Indiana Beach campgrounds had been sold to Morgan RV LLC.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/2013/12/29/worries-grow-about-indiana-beach-future/4244841/|title=Worries grow about Indiana Beach future|last=Livingston|first=Mikel|date=December 29, 2013|website=IndyStar|access-date=}}</ref> On September 1, 2015, it was announced that the park had been sold to Apex Parks Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2016/03/06/indiana-beachs-new-owner-overhauling-amusement-park/81418512/|title=Indiana Beach\u2019s new owner overhauling amusement park|last=AP|first=|date=March 6, 2016|website=IndyStar|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screamscape.com/html/indiana_beach.htm|title=Indiana Beach|last=|first=|date=|website=www.screamscape.com|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 18, 2020, Indiana Beach announced that it would permanently close after 94 years of operation, with no plans to reopen. Apex Parks Group cited financial reasons for the closure and said they had \u201cworked diligently\u201d to find a new buyer for the park but were not successful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wlfi.com/content/news/Indiana-Beach-closes-gates-567980101.html|title=Indiana Beach Closes After Nearly a Century|last=AP|first=|date=February 18, 2020|website=[[WLFI]]|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In addition to dozens of seasonal workers, Indiana Beach employed 27 people in administrative and maintenance positions. Those workers were offered six weeks compensation.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wthr.com/article/indiana-beach-close-after-94-years|title=Indiana Beach to Close after 94 Years|last=AP|first=|date=February 18, 2020|website=[[WTHR]]|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Apex Parks Group said that it was in discussions with potential buyers of the park, and that it was possible that the park would be able to reopen this year. Because Indiana Beach generates a large part of the county's tourism revenue, [[White County, Indiana|White County]] officials have agreed to offer $3 million from the White County Windfarm Economic Development Fund to the buyer after the sale is complete.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.ibj.com/articles/owner-indiana-beach-amusement-park-could-reopen-this-year|title=Owner: Indiana Beach amusement park could reopen this year|date=March 22, 2020|work=[[Indianapolis Business Journal]]|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Indiana Beach announced that the park would be reopening that year. The park was reportedly bought by Gene Staples, a former US Navy Veteran currently based in Chicago who is now the president of Indiana Beach Holdings.\n\n==Rides==\n[[Image:IBeach ShaferQueen DSCN9212.JPG|right|thumb|250px|Shafer Queen]]\n[[Image:IBeach HurricaneDrop DSCN9199.JPG|right|thumb|250px|Hoosier Hurricane]]\n[[Image:Flyers-IndianaBeach.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Air Crow]]\n[[Image:IB-fascination.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Carnival Games]]\n\n===Roller coasters===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Type !! Design !! Year Opened !! Year Closed !! Manufacturer\n|-\n| [[Cornball Express]] || Wood || Twister || 2001 ||  ||[[Custom Coasters International|CCI]]\n|-\n| [[Hoosier Hurricane]] || Wood || Out and Back || 1994 ||  ||[[Custom Coasters International|CCI]]\n|-\n| [[Lost Coaster of Superstition Mountain]] || Wood || Elevator Lift || 2002 ||  ||[[Custom 